In this article, President Barack Obama declares April as National Cancer Control Month. He acknowledges the progress made in fighting cancer but emphasizes that there is still work to be done. He encourages individuals to take steps to reduce their chances of developing cancer, such as maintaining a healthy weight, protecting skin from UV radiation, limiting alcohol consumption, and quitting smoking. The President also highlights the importance of early detection and mentions the Affordable Care Act's provisions for coverage of preventive services and eliminating coverage limits and denials based on pre-existing conditions. He discusses the Precision Medicine Initiative, which aims to revolutionize how the nation combats disease by tailoring treatments to individual patients. The President calls for remembering those lost to cancer and recognizes the efforts of individuals and organizations dedicated to advancing the fight against cancer. He urges citizens, government agencies, businesses, and nonprofit organizations to participate in activities that raise awareness about cancer prevention and control.